post_text:
Today we remember all those who were lost or affected by the tragedy of 9/11, and thank those who served our nation during our time of need.

In memory of the 2,974 lives lost, here is an excerpt from Billy Collin‚Äôs poem ‚ÄúThe Names‚Äù, which he based on the events from 9/11:

‚ÄúNames of citizens, workers, mothers and fathers,
The bright-eyed daughter, the quick son.
Alphabet of names in a green field.
Names in the small tracks of birds.
Names lifted from a hat
Or balanced on the tip of the tongue.
Names wheeled into the dim warehouse of memory.
So many names, there is barely room on the walls of the heart.‚Äù

#NeverForget

post_text:
In 1776, a small committee including Thomas Jefferson, Benjamin Franklin, and John Adams was tasked with writing a formal statement of the colonies‚Äô intention to declare their independence from Great Britain. In just over a month, that statement was formally adopted by the Continental Congress in Philadelphia as the Declaration of Independence. Here‚Äôs an interesting fact that many don‚Äôt know: while the committee consisted of 5 men, Thomas Jefferson wrote most of the Declaration of Independence!

Happy Fourth of July everyone! üá∫üá∏

post_text: #FunFactFriday - The # symbol isn't officially called a hashtag or pound sign; its technical name is octothorpe! The "octo-" means "eight" to refer to its points, though reports disagree on where "-thorpe" came from. Some claim it was named after Olympian Jim Thorpe, while others argue it was just a nonsense suffix.

post_text:
Important Message for our Charger Families & Students,

It's been brought to our attention that there may be some type of meet-up planned for students this evening in order to see one another before the Stay-At-Home order goes into effect tonight at 5pm, and that this meet-up will take place on school property. We wanted to take a moment to remind everyone about the social distancing guidelines in place in the U.S., as well as to encourage you to review CDC recommendations and guidelines on how to best contain the spread of COVID-19. As you know, our schools are closed for the safety of our families and staff, and as of yesterday our Governor and Superintendent extended the closure of school through the end of the year. Please know that if any meet-up were to take place, this would not be a school-sanctioned event. We encourage everyone to stay home, and stay safe!

post_text: In addition to some of the other food bank information we‚Äôve previously shared, we wanted to pass along this information about the Help Yourself program being offered by United Food Bank in Mesa.
shared_text:
United Food Bank
March 19 at 12:33 PM ¬∑

Food will be available through our Help Yourself program this Friday, 8 a.m. to noon, at 358 E. Javelina Ave. in Mesa.

We will be distributing food there every Friday at no charge until further notice. This week, we are also continuing measures to reduce the risk of spreading germs:

There will be NO PARKING at the Volunteer Center Parking Lot. Please review the map for parking in the GREEN AREA in the comments below.

Our building will be closed to the public. Please sign in outside in front of the entrance to the Volunteer Center, then volunteers will help deliver a pre-loaded cart filled with frozen meat, fresh produce and other items to the trunk of your vehicle.

Again, if you are feeling any cold or flu symptoms--especially cough, fever or shortness of breath--we ask you to stay at home and seek treatment so you can get better.

Thank you!

Our building will be closed to the public. Please sign in outside in front of the entrance to the Volunteer Center, then volunteers will help deliver a pre-loaded cart filled with frozen meat, fresh produce and other items to the trunk of your vehicle.

Again, if you are feeling any cold or flu symptoms--especially cough, fever or shortness of breath--we ask you to stay at home and seek treatment so you can get better.

Thank you!

Our high school Student Government is hosting a Charity Week next week (February 3-7th) in support of FANS Across America, an organization that helps provide daily living necessities to homeless students, families in transition, victims and children of domestic violence.

To raise money for this organization, there will be a Charity Carnival on Friday, February 7th from 4-7pm with food trucks, carnival games, live music, raffle prizes, face painting, obstacle courses, and more at our high school campus. We are excited to offer this community event to all friends and family of our BFCS community.

Admission to the Carnival is $2 for individuals and $10 for large families. Game tickets will be sold as well: 5 tickets for $3 and 10 tickets for $5.

post_text: #FunFactFriday Holiday Edition: Did you know that hanging stockings started by accident? According to legend, it started with a poor man who didn't have the money for his three daughters' dowries. Generous old St. Nick dropped a bag of gold down their chimney - where the girls had hung their stockings to dry by the fire. That's where the gold ended up, and allegedly how the tradition began.

It's #GivingTuesday! GivingTuesday is a global generosity movement unleashing the power of people and organizations to transform their communities and the world on December 3, 2019 and every day. We are so thankful for our parents, students, staff, teachers, and community members, and for all they do throughout the year. One way people can help our school is by donating - when you donate to our school, you help provide our students with top notch extra-curricular activities! Plus, you are eligible to receive a Tax Credit when donating to our school (a tax credit is, in effect, a full refund of your money).

If you would like to donate to our school, please visit https://donorbox.org/bfcsaz-2, and thank you for your generosity!

post_text:
This Saturday, December 7th, we are administering the Classic Learning Test at Benjamin Franklin High School. The CLT is a rapidly growing standardized college admissions exam designed to offer a rigorous testing experience. It presents classic material using an innovative medium: an online exam which provides students with same-day results and eligibility for over $100 million in scholarships.

Registration is open to any high school student, not just BFHS students. Please visit www.cltexam.com to create an account and register. Be sure to share with others you may know! Last chance to register for the Dec. 7th test date is tomorrow, December 3rd.
